entry.title: [Lacros] Fail fast if TabStripModel adds same observer twice
entry.content:
In crbug.com/1427990, TabStripModel was added to the same observer

twice, which led to an eventual NOTREACHED(). Unfortunately, because of

ICF (Identical Code Folding), the stacktrace was not particularly useful

for helping the developers find the culprit. While the NOTREACHED()

statement is doing a decent job in guarding against unexpected code

path, further investigation is needed to figure out what goes wrong in

the higher UI and business logic level.



This CL adds a CHECK() to assist future investigation only for the

Lacros platform, in the hope that consumers and dogfooders can submit

not only stacktraces but also what user actions they perform before

crashes happen. Only for Lacros is because the majority of the crashes

were only observed in the Lacros platform.

entry.title: [lacros] Fix memory leak in client test globals.
entry.content:
Seems the root cause is that the Globals class used for testing does not

properly handle having more than one wl_output instances, which is

relatively common when testing multi-display scenarios, like the

WaylandDisplayOutputTest. This started having a memory leak after

crrev.com/c/4471787 was checked in, with the critical line being binding

the zaura_output_manager in globals.cc.



It's unclear why this additional binding triggered the memory leak,

whereas before this, no leak was detected by lsan.



The fix is to make Globals class properly hold all wl_output instances,

instead of destroying earlier instances whenever a new output is added.

entry.title: AddressTrackerLinux: Fix race condition setting SequencedTaskRunner
entry.content:
Chrome's main thread runs AddressTrackerLinux::SetDiffCallback(), which

posts a task to the AddressTrackerLinux's `sequenced_task_runner_`. But

`sequenced_task_runner_` is initialized on AddressTrackerLinux's

sequence in AddressTrackerLinux::Init(). So the main thread may win

the race and post to a null SequencedTaskRunner.



Fix by having the owner of the AddressTrackerLinux,

NetworkChangeNotifierLinux, construct the AddressTrackerLinux with the

correct SequencedTaskRunner.

defaults



Due to subtleties of group-based policies a correctly set default

handler might in some cases be missing (a single user might inherit

error -- instead the decision is delegated to the normal flow.

entry.title: EditContext: Handle WebLocalFrameImpl::FirstRectForCharacterRange
entry.content:
On Mac, when there is an active composition for an EditContext and

the author has not called updateCharacterBounds before the next call

to RenderWidgetHostViewCocoa firstRectForCharacterRange, the browser

process will fall back to calling

WebLocalFrameImpl::FirstRectForCharacterRange in the render process.



This function does not take EditContext into account, and will try

to find the right rect by positioning a range in the DOM, which will

often produce an entirely wrong result if the composition is

happening in an EditContext.



Fix this by implementing FirstRectForCharacterRange for EditContext.

First we attempt to use the character bounds provided by the author,

but fallback to using the control bounds if characterBounds are

not available.

entry.title: [Tab Switcher] Replace RoundedCornerImageView with custom impl
entry.content:
Replace TabGridThumbnailView's RoundCornerImageView with a

custom implementation that better handles vector & layer drawables,

a persistent background, etc.



An attempt was made to use

* ShapeableImageView - This is inconsistent when drawing to canvases

backed by hardware vs software due to its draw then clear approach.

It seems to work fine outside of RenderTests, but due to risks with

OEMs or forced software vs hardware draw implementations it is risky.

* RoundedCornerImageView - This has other clients. The implementation

is quite complicated and its behavior for background vs foreground

is very messy for trying to layer on a Vector or Layer Drawable

instead of a Bitmap as it primarily uses a BitmapShader to apply the

rounded corner effect. It is simpler in the generic case to add a

clipPath and GradientDrawable to an ImageView.
